ce:section.ce:para:
The morphology and surface structure of graphene quantum dots (GQDs) and functionalized graphene quantum dot catalysts were investigated using scanning electron microscopy[48] and transmission electron microscopy [49] techniques (Fig. 6
                     ). The SEM images reveal that the average particle size of the GQDs formed is 17–35 nm, exhibiting spherical shapes (Fig. 6A-B). Following the post-synthesis modification of functionalized GQDs, the average particle size increases to about 42–73 nm (Fig. 6C-D). The TEM image, after the post-synthesis modification process, demonstrates the presence of well-dispersed cobalt, over the surface of GQDs@SiO3Pr-Schiff base/Co (II) complex (Fig. 6E-F). Additionally, the particle size of the synthesized functionalized graphene quantum dots (FGQDs) was calculated, and the results are presented in Fig. 7
                     . This figure indicates a mean particle size of 53 nm.

EDS and EDS mapping analysis are employed to examine the elemental composition and spatial distribution of elements in the final composite (Fig. 8
                     ). EDS analysis verifies the presence of oxygen, carbon, nitrogen, silicon, and cobalt in the GQDs@SiO3Pr-Schiff base/Co (II) complex catalyst, with a cobalt loading of 16.62 wt.%. Furthermore, EDS mapping demonstrates a uniform dispersion of elements within the sample matrix, thus confirming the successful formation of the catalyst (Fig. 9
                     ).
